00:47:35.160 --> 00:47:38.050
You are statistically
insignificant.

00:47:38.050 --> 00:47:40.930
Even if what you're saying is
identical to the mainstream

00:47:40.930 --> 00:47:43.270
views, it's just the phrasing.

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:44.570
So that's really key.

00:47:44.570 --> 00:47:47.556
Also, if you can back up any of
the things you find wrong

00:47:47.556 --> 00:47:49.620
with it with irrefutable
principles, then you're

00:47:49.620 --> 00:47:53.260
actually having a debate on the
actual design, as opposed

00:47:53.260 --> 00:47:54.770
to opinions.

00:47:54.770 --> 00:47:57.720
We don't see opinion debates in
engineering as much because

00:47:57.720 --> 00:47:59.810
you have these irrefutable
principles like, something

00:47:59.810 --> 00:48:01.710
shouldn't crash, or it shouldn't
use too much memory,

00:48:01.710 --> 00:48:02.860
or it should be fast.

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:06.310
So if you start grounding things
in mode errors, or

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:11.040
consistency, or the user being
able to find help if they need

00:48:11.040 --> 00:48:15.490
it, things that everyone agrees
should be right, then

00:48:15.490 --> 00:48:17.920
it's not really a debate as much
as you just pointing out

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.880
a bug that they need to fix.

00:48:20.880 --> 00:48:22.130
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:23.920 --> 00:48:26.120
AUDIENCE: I've worked on
projects with dedicated

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:28.610
designers, and then I've also
worked on projects that are

00:48:28.610 --> 00:48:31.020
just a bunch of engineers
making something that

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:33.350
inevitably ends up
looking horrible.

00:48:33.350 --> 00:48:37.390
Do you have any suggestions when
you have just engineers

00:48:37.390 --> 00:48:40.910
working on a project, and any
things that they could do,

00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:42.770
when they know they're making
something that's not

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:47.340
well-designed, what to do to
help improve the design?

00:48:47.340 --> 00:48:51.470
ALEX FAABORG: Well, hiring an
agency is always an option.

00:48:51.470 --> 00:48:54.390
People often discount that as
too expensive, or they haven't

00:48:54.390 --> 00:48:56.680
done it before so they
haven't tried it, it

00:48:56.680 --> 00:48:57.450
works really well.

00:48:57.450 --> 00:49:00.540
And also, you often see a lot
of the return in having a

00:49:00.540 --> 00:49:02.400
[INAUDIBLE] designed thing
if you're selling the

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:03.440
application.

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:06.320
If you're just doing it
yourself, trying to isolate

00:49:06.320 --> 00:49:09.570
your mind and look at it from
the perspective of a user.

00:49:09.570 --> 00:49:13.680
If you are able to, show it to
other people that haven't seen

00:49:13.680 --> 00:49:15.390
it before, and do sort
of quick tests.

00:49:15.390 --> 00:49:17.910
I Ask them to think out loud as
they're interacting with it

00:49:17.910 --> 00:49:20.010
so you can hear their
thought process.

00:49:20.010 --> 00:49:22.460
Sometimes everyone's so secret
about their stuff that you

00:49:22.460 --> 00:49:24.120
can't do that.

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:26.212
So that's really important.

00:49:26.212 --> 00:49:27.800
Do you have other suggestions?

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:31.600
CHRISTIAN ROBINSON: Another
thing for independent

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:34.650
developers that don't have a
very big staff is that for a

00:49:34.650 --> 00:49:37.520
lot of these platforms, there
is a lot of work that's done

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:40.420
into making the platform and
making those pieces so that

00:49:40.420 --> 00:49:44.520
they work and do the
right thing.

00:49:44.520 --> 00:49:48.390
So looking at the platform
itself and kind of figuring

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:50.920
out the standard way that the
platform does things is a

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:54.100
really good way to get
oftentimes a good portion of

00:49:54.100 --> 00:49:55.020
the way there.

00:49:55.020 --> 00:49:56.130
ALEX FAABORG: Also reading
the style guide, I

00:49:56.130 --> 00:49:57.070
should mention that.

00:49:57.070 --> 00:49:59.320
Android has a great style
guide that we both

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:00.760
worked on, so biased.

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:03.440
But what's nice about it is it
doesn't just give you the

00:50:03.440 --> 00:50:04.840
various principles, but it also
gives you kind of the

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:06.810
thinking behind all of them.

00:50:06.810 --> 00:50:09.890
And it's not like a rule book
as much as guidelines so you

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:12.130
can understand, this is why
this will make your

00:50:12.130 --> 00:50:13.770
application better as you
follow these various

00:50:13.770 --> 00:50:14.020
guidelines.

00:50:14.020 --> 00:50:15.820
CHRISTIAN ROBINSON: It's some
kind of another instance of

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:17.070
line stuff up.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:23.280
Don't reinvent a new way to do a
list unless there's a really

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:24.530
good reason to.

00:50:27.590 --> 00:50:31.080
Unless it really changes the
character of your thing and

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:34.960
there's a purpose, there's no
reason to invent a new kind of

00:50:34.960 --> 00:50:36.210
scroll bar.

00:50:41.600 --> 00:50:44.120
AUDIENCE: For the Android design
style guideline, I was

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:48.420
wondering what you guys foresee
in terms of how its

00:50:48.420 --> 00:50:51.320
evolution is going to be over
time, especially with phone

00:50:51.320 --> 00:50:52.800
devices, mobile devices.

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:54.640
The screen size is getting
larger, and a lot of times

00:50:54.640 --> 00:50:56.630
I've heard that you want to
keep things closer to your

00:50:56.630 --> 00:50:59.000
thumb, but with things like the
Action Bar Menu and the

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.280
Overflow Menu, it's so far away
on a large device that

00:51:01.280 --> 00:51:03.330
you no longer have the
ability to easily

00:51:03.330 --> 00:51:04.970
do single hand actions.

00:51:04.970 --> 00:51:05.320
ALEX FAABORG: Yeah.

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:07.140
Well, on large devices you
have the radius of

00:51:07.140 --> 00:51:08.400
thumbs on the edges.

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:10.800
You want to definitely
think about that.

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:13.780
And the style guide, it's
evolving as fast as the

00:51:13.780 --> 00:51:15.290
ecosystem and the devices are.

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:17.690
We're constantly pushing out
updates, considering new

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:18.730
patterns, things like that.

00:51:18.730 --> 00:51:21.440
So it's not like this sort of
fixed thing that everyone has

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:25.580
to adhere to as much as a kind
of organic living document as

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:26.990
we all collectively
learn more.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.340
AUDIENCE: Thank you for the
phone number slide.

00:51:33.340 --> 00:51:34.440
I really like that.

00:51:34.440 --> 00:51:39.060
It reminded me of one of the
horrible failures of iTunes

00:51:39.060 --> 00:51:42.340
that I've just been
annoyed by.

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:47.200
If you have a date, and you
format it with four numbers, a

00:51:47.200 --> 00:51:52.100
dash, two numbers, a dash, and
two numbers more, that should

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:56.340
be in ISO format for
year, month, day,

