00:52:15.530 --> 00:52:17.455
you're familiar with, but
knowing who you're designing

00:52:17.455 --> 00:52:18.705
for is really important.

00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:23.760
AUDIENCE: I do have a
question this time.

00:52:23.760 --> 00:52:25.780
Can you talk about tools
a little bit?

00:52:25.780 --> 00:52:28.360
I mean, Photoshop is the obvious
one, but what other

00:52:28.360 --> 00:52:29.880
tools can you talk about?

00:52:29.880 --> 00:52:31.940
ALEX FAABORG: So I really
like Fireworks.

00:52:31.940 --> 00:52:33.790
It has more direct manipulation
of the objects,

00:52:33.790 --> 00:52:36.712
you can actually do nine
slice symbols in it.

00:52:36.712 --> 00:52:38.510
A lot of people use OmniGraffe
or Keynote.

00:52:43.140 --> 00:52:44.570
For OmniGraffe and Fireworks,
we have stencils.

00:52:44.570 --> 00:52:49.600
We also have a Photoshop stencil
for Android design.

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:52.490
Really, the granularity of your
mock-ups has a lot to do

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:56.240
with how final you want people
to think they are.

00:52:56.240 --> 00:52:59.020
So if you show someone a
full-fidelity mock-up and ask

00:52:59.020 --> 00:53:00.870
their opinions, they're going
to start commenting on the

00:53:00.870 --> 00:53:02.800
colors and those types
of aspects.

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:04.620
If you show them a wire frame,
they're going to start

00:53:04.620 --> 00:53:07.850
commenting on the organization
of the information, how you

00:53:07.850 --> 00:53:09.230
flow through the application.

00:53:09.230 --> 00:53:11.350
So it's important to create the
mock-up at the level of

00:53:11.350 --> 00:53:14.870
fidelity of the feedback
that you want.

00:53:14.870 --> 00:53:18.350
Otherwise, really just sketching
stuff on paper is a

00:53:18.350 --> 00:53:21.440
very quick, fast way
of conveying ideas.

00:53:21.440 --> 00:53:23.270
Early in the process, it's
about how many different

00:53:23.270 --> 00:53:25.840
designs you can come up with
as opposed to creating a

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:30.600
perfect one, so that's also
important to consider.

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:34.540
AUDIENCE: A little bit taboo,
but a lot of us have apps that

00:53:34.540 --> 00:53:37.650
are on multiple platforms,
like iOS as well.

00:53:37.650 --> 00:53:42.200
I just wanted to see what
comments you might have on

00:53:42.200 --> 00:53:46.606
like where I work,
there's like a--

00:53:46.606 --> 00:53:49.750
to try to get it completely the
same on both, and there's

00:53:49.750 --> 00:53:52.960
a lot of directions that
designers want to go to

00:53:52.960 --> 00:53:54.330
consistency versus [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:54.330 --> 00:53:55.150
for the platforms?

00:53:55.150 --> 00:53:56.370
So I just kind of wanted
to see what your

00:53:56.370 --> 00:53:58.250
comments are there.

00:53:58.250 --> 00:54:01.020
CHRISTIAN ROBINSON: This is one
that comes up quite a bit

00:54:01.020 --> 00:54:03.020
for designers in
this industry.

00:54:03.020 --> 00:54:09.160
And the way that I think about
it is, from the product to

00:54:09.160 --> 00:54:13.730
designer's point of view, what
we're dealing with is all of

00:54:13.730 --> 00:54:16.760
these products across the
different platforms.

00:54:16.760 --> 00:54:19.700
And so the first instinct is to
design everything exactly

00:54:19.700 --> 00:54:22.340
the same because, and yes, it
works the same across all the

00:54:22.340 --> 00:54:23.440
different platforms.

00:54:23.440 --> 00:54:26.480
But from the user's point of
view, there are some users

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:29.350
that have three different
phone platforms in their

00:54:29.350 --> 00:54:32.260
pocket at all times,
that's uncommon.

00:54:32.260 --> 00:54:35.100
More often, users will have
one platform, and they're

00:54:35.100 --> 00:54:37.740
using all of these different
parts of the platform.

00:54:37.740 --> 00:54:40.870
And so when they're looking
for something to hang onto

00:54:40.870 --> 00:54:43.250
from a consistency standpoint,
they're expecting things to

00:54:43.250 --> 00:54:44.910
work like the platform.

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:49.430
So when you create an app that's
consistent for you but

00:54:49.430 --> 00:54:54.845
not consistent for your user,
then it's maybe not making the

00:54:54.845 --> 00:54:55.900
right choice.

00:54:55.900 --> 00:54:58.620
So designing for the specific
platforms and designing for

00:54:58.620 --> 00:55:03.440
those conventions, it's a
challenge to find a way to

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:06.980
express your brand across all
those platforms, but--

00:55:06.980 --> 00:55:08.180
ALEX FAABORG: Also, your brand
should be stronger

00:55:08.180 --> 00:55:09.130
than just the UI.

00:55:09.130 --> 00:55:10.710
It's kind of silly if the
UI is your brand.

00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:13.120
Your brand is about the
emotional connection people

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:14.775
have to your application, and
your colors, and watermark,

00:55:14.775 --> 00:55:16.230
and things like that.

00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:19.030
And then also, Christian
concluded his talk with

00:55:19.030 --> 00:55:22.680
showing users that you care, and
also talking about how a

00:55:22.680 --> 00:55:25.620
poorly-designed icon, does that
application crash more?

00:55:25.620 --> 00:55:27.680
Your application, you could care
a lot about it, but if

00:55:27.680 --> 00:55:29.950
it's identical to the other
platforms, it kind of looks

00:55:29.950 --> 00:55:31.370
like it was quickly
ported over.

00:55:31.370 --> 00:55:34.600
It doesn't convey that level
of effort, and people are

00:55:34.600 --> 00:55:36.980
going to see that and make
judgments off of how much

00:55:36.980 --> 00:55:38.230
effort you put into it.

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:45.540
It's kind of a negative
note to end it on.

00:55:45.540 --> 00:55:46.790
All right, well thank
you for coming.

